The Joint Admissions and Matriculation Board (JAMB) has delisted an additional six Computer Based Centres (CBT) over poor performance on the second day of the 2021 Unified Tertiary Matriculation Examination (UTME). Dr Fabian Benjamin, Head, Protocol and Public Affairs of JAMB, disclosed this in a statement made available to newsmen in Abuja on Tuesday, NAN reports. Benjamin said candidates who were unable to register during the allowable time for registration despite the extension were directed to visit designated centres to be registered. He said these categories of candidates that had been scheduled for the 2021 UTME were directed to print their examination notification slip for their schedule for the examination from June 21. 2021 UTME: JAMB delists 25 CBT centres over poor performance (see list)
He, however, directed the candidates to print their notification slip from the JAMB’s website www.jamb.gov.ng. According to him, 464,834 candidates across the country wrote the UTME on June 21, the second day of the examination. He gave the names of the additional delisted centres to include: -Dayspring Christian College, Opete town near Otokutu between Ughelli South lga and Udu Local Government, Delta -Fountain of Knowledge International Academy CBT, Azuiyiokwu, Abakaliki, Ebonyi State. – Twelve Apostles College, Ndiaboishiagu Sharon, Abakaliki, Ebonyi State. – Lead British International School, 1 Aliyu Mustdafa Street, off Wole Soyinka Street, Gwarimpa, Abuja, FCT. – Zaria Academy, Km 10, Zaria-Funtua road, Shika, Zaria in Kaduna State. 2021 UTME: JAMB gives new instruction to candidates of delisted centres
– Muhammed Kamaldeen CBT centre proposed Muhammed Kamaldeen University along FGC, Ogidi, Ilorin in Kwara. Recall that the board had earlier delisted 24 CBT centres across the country over poor performance at the commencement of the 2021 UTME. The new additional centres bring the total number of delisted centres across the country to 30.